objects.name: Crooked Pisces
objects.description: Crooked Pisces AKA KONNI, is a threat group operating in East Asia. This group is known for using spear-phishing attacks with documents related to North Korea, but lately, documents related to cryptocurrency also have been observed. Crooked Pisces is also the name of their custom RAT which leverages anti-analysis techniques and intelligence gathering features.

objects.name: SkySky Campaign
objects.description: Crooked Pisces Group sent a spear-phishing email with malicious attachments, using an account name SkySky. The threat group uses macros to communicate with the C2 server and download additional required files that install the final malicious payload. This campaign was targeted South Korean users in the Financial industry.

objects.name: Eurasia Campaign
objects.description: Beginning in early 2018, Unit 42 observed a series of attacks using a previously unreported malware family, NOKKI.  The malware in question has ties to a previously reported malware family named KONNI. The latest activity leveraging the NOKKI payload likely targets politically-motivated victims in Eurasia and possibly Southeast Asia. These attacks leverage compromised legitimate infrastructure for both delivery and command and control (C2). These compromised servers are largely located within South Korea.

objects.name: Fractured Statue Campaign
objects.description: Between July and October of 2019, Unit 42 observed continued several malware families typically associated with the Crooked Pisces Group used to primarily target a US government agency. The malware families consisted mainly of malicious documents featuring CARROTBAT downloaders with SYSCON payloads but also included a new malware downloader Unit 42 has dubbed CARROTBALL.  Unit 42 assesses with moderate confidence that this activity is related to the Crooked Pisces Group.

objects.name: Cryptomining HWP Campaign
objects.description: Crooked Pisces Group sent spear-phishing emails with malicious attachments. Vulnerable HWP documents that contained malicious scripts command hidden inside the document. Crooked Pisces was targetting South Korean users that were interested in cryptocurrency mining. The contents of the attached documents were cryptocurrency transactions and other information related to crypto mining.

objects.name: SYSCON
objects.description: The malware is effectively a file stealer which uses the FTP protocol to exfiltrate files from targeted machines, as well as to receive and execute new commands.

objects.name: NOKKI
objects.description: NOKKI is a malware family that has been found to have code overlap with the KONNI malware family. The malware originally was found to communicate via FTP for command and control (C2) channels. However, beginning in July 2018 it was observed switching to HTTP for C2 communication. NOKKI is modular in nature, allowing attackers to upload and execute various modules based on the actions required for a given victim. File manager and information collection modules have been observed being served to this malware family.

objects.name: CARROTBAT
objects.description: CARROTBAT is a dropper and downloader malware family that is responsible for both displaying an embedded decoy document, as well as downloading and executing a remote payload.  This malware family has been used delivering lures commonly associated with the Southeast Asia region.

objects.name: CARROTBALL
objects.description: CARROTBALL is a simple FTP-based downloader first found embedded in a targeted macro document associated with Crooked Pisces activity as part of the Fractured Statue campaign. Its most common observed payload is the Syscon backdoor.
